Introduction

During the first three weeks, you learned a couple of essential notions and theorems, and one of the most important among them is the Bayes theorem.

One of its applications is Naive Bayes classifier, which is a probabilistic classifier whose aim is to determine which class some observation probably belongs to by using the Bayes formula: \[\mathsf{P}(\mathrm{class}\mid \mathrm{observation})=\frac{\mathsf{P}(\mathrm{observation}\mid\mathrm{class})\mathsf{P}(\mathrm{class})}{\mathsf{P}(\mathrm{observation})}\]

Under the strong independence assumption, one can calculate \(\mathsf{P}(\mathrm{observation} \mid \mathrm{class})\) as \[\mathsf{P}(\mathrm{observation}) = \prod_{i=1}^{n} \mathsf{P}(\mathrm{feature}_i), \qquad \mathsf{P}(\mathrm{observation} \mid \mathrm{class}) = \prod_{i=1}^{n} \mathsf{P}(\mathrm{feature}_i \mid \mathrm{class}),\] where \(n\) is the total number of features describing a given observation. Thus, \(\mathsf{P}(\mathrm{class}|\mathrm{observation})\) now can be calculated as

\[\mathsf{P}(\mathrm{class} \mid \mathrm{\mathrm{observation}}) = \mathsf{P}(\mathrm{class})\times \prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{\mathsf{P}(\mathrm{feature}_i\mid \mathrm{class})}{\mathsf{P}(\mathrm{feature}_i)}\tag{1}\]

All the terms on the right-hand side can be estimated from the data as respective relative frequencies;
*see this site for more detailed explanations*

clean_text <- function(text) {
  text <- tolower(text)
  text <- gsub("[[:punct:][:digit:]+]", "", text)
  text <- trimws(text)
  words <- unlist(strsplit(text, "\\s+"))
  return (text)
}


remove_stop_words <- function(text, stop_words) {
  words <- unlist(strsplit(text, "\\s+"))
  cleaned_words <- words[!words %in% stop_words]
  cleaned_text <- paste(cleaned_words, collapse = " ")
  cleaned_text <- trimws(cleaned_text)  # remove white-spaces, just in case
  return(cleaned_text)
}

make_tidier <- function(train, col) {
  tidy_text <- unnest_tokens(train, 'Word', col, token="words")
  tidy_text %>% count(Word,sort=TRUE)
}

Data visualization

Each time you work with some data, you need to understand it before you start processing it. R has very powerful tools to make nice plots and visualization. Show what are the most common words for negative and positive examples as a histogram, word cloud etc. Be creative!

plot_frequency <- function(data_set_name, min_frequency) {
  if (data_set_name == "credible") {
    filtered_words <- credible_news_frequencies[credible_news_frequencies$n >= min_frequency, ]
  } else if (data_set_name == "fake") {
    filtered_words <- fake_news_frequencies[fake_news_frequencies$n >= min_frequency, ]
  } else if (data_set_name == "total") {
    filtered_words <- data_total_frequencies[data_total_frequencies$n >= min_frequency, ]
  } else {
    stop("'data_set_name' should equal 'credible', 'fake' or 'total'")
  }

  p <- ggplot(filtered_words, aes(x = reorder(Word, -n), y = n)) +
    geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
    labs(x = "Words", y = "Word Count") +
    ggtitle(sprintf(
      "Word Frequencies. News type: %s (Frequency >= %s )",
      data_set_name,
      min_frequency)) + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

  plot(p)

  ggsave(sprintf(
    "%s_word_frequencies_%s.pdf",
    data_set_name,
    min_frequency), p)
}

Classifier implementation

credible_words <- credible_news_frequencies
fake_words <- fake_news_frequencies


all_unique_words <- nrow(data_total_frequencies)


prediction_of_message <- function(newmessage, data_current, unique_quantity) 
  {
  
      current_words <- sum(data_current$n)
    
      words <- c()
      numbers <- c()
      
      message <- unlist(strsplit(newmessage, split = " "))
      for (x in message) {
        words <- c(words, x)
        if (!(x %in% data_current$Word)) {
          numbers <- c(numbers, 0)
        } else {
          idx <- which(data_current$Word==x)
          numbers <- c(numbers, data_current$n[idx[1]])
        }
      }
      need_data <- data.frame(Words = words, n = numbers)
      
      #Calculating probability that message is credible/fake (depends on request)
      res <- 1
      for (x in message){
        idx <- which(need_data$Word==x)
        prob <- ((need_data$n[idx[1]] + 1)/ (current_words + unique_quantity))
        res <- res * prob
      }
    
          return(res)
    }
    
    
check_message <- function(message, all_unique_words, credible_words, fake_words)
  {
      # Determines whether message is credible or fake
      prob_credible <- prediction_of_message(message, credible_words, all_unique_words)
      prob_fake <- prediction_of_message(message, fake_words, all_unique_words)
      
      label <- "fake"
      if (prob_credible > prob_fake){
        label <- "credible"
      }
      return(label)
    }
    
    
result <- c()
for (message in data_test_body){
  label <- check_message(message, all_unique_words, credible_words, fake_words)
  result <- c(result, label)
}

Conclusions

Shakespeare would have said: Shame on thee, thou who neglect the chances!

As we have just discovered, despite claiming that probability in real life is pretty useless, actually there are fields that make knowledge of P&S bloom in its various colours. One can believe that the understanding of probability will never come in handy, yet its showtime begins unexpectedly.

One could never guess that such thing as determining whether the news is fake or credible We used to think, that it was pure luck. Although the calculations may not be perfect due to value loss in R language, in general we can proudly announce that probability theory has successfully proved its own usefulness.

The real life example was the best teacher and the myth-buster: not a single soul would dare to day that P&S is of no use. Even though the field may be sometimes complicated and difficult to comprehend, our team can say that thanks to P&S we can distinguish fake and credible news :)

So, briefly about the magic we utilised Naive Bayes classifier and Laplace smoothing. Long talk shortly, the method allows us to determine the right category of incoming data based on previously provided data by splitting up the input into simple parts. Firstly we clean the text: make everything lower case, remove punctuation marks and digits, delete stop-words (words that do not have any valuable information). After that, we divide the text into separate words. The idea of Naive Bayes is that we calculate how many times each word occurs in each category (in our case fake or credible); then we calculate the probability that exactly current word belongs to each category, and then combine all the probabilities.

However, its possible that the word might never occur in a category, which will lead to probability nullification. To avoid this, we use Laplace smoothing: we add 1 to numerator, and number of unique words in whole data set to the denominator. Only after smoothing we may proceed calculating probabilities.
